🔎 Initial Array
Code
[38, 27, 43, 3, 9, 82, 10]
Step 1: Divide
Left = 0, Right = 6 → Mid = 3

Split into two halves:

Left half: [38, 27, 43, 3]

Right half: [9, 82, 10]

Step 2: Recursively Divide Left Half [38, 27, 43, 3]
Left = 0, Right = 3 → Mid = 1

Split into:

[38, 27]

[43, 3]

Further divide [38, 27]
Left = 0, Right = 1 → Mid = 0

Split into [38] and [27]

Merge → [27, 38]

Further divide [43, 3]
Left = 2, Right = 3 → Mid = 2

Split into [43] and [3]

Merge → [3, 43]

Merge [27, 38] and [3, 43]
Compare elements:

27 vs 3 → pick 3

27 vs 43 → pick 27

38 vs 43 → pick 38

Remaining → 43

Result → [3, 27, 38, 43]

Step 3: Recursively Divide Right Half [9, 82, 10]
Left = 4, Right = 6 → Mid = 5

Split into:

[9, 82]

[10]

Further divide [9, 82]
Left = 4, Right = 5 → Mid = 4

Split into [9] and [82]

Merge → [9, 82]

Merge [9, 82] and [10]
Compare elements:

9 vs 10 → pick 9

82 vs 10 → pick 10

Remaining → 82

Result → [9, 10, 82]

Step 4: Final Merge
Merge [3, 27, 38, 43] and [9, 10, 82]

Compare elements:

3 vs 9 → pick 3

27 vs 9 → pick 9

27 vs 10 → pick 10

27 vs 82 → pick 27

38 vs 82 → pick 38

43 vs 82 → pick 43

Remaining → 82

Result → [3, 9, 10, 27, 38, 43, 82]

✅ Final Sorted Array
Code
[3, 9, 10, 27, 38, 43, 82]
Key Observations
Merge Sort keeps splitting until single elements remain.

Then it merges back in sorted order.

Time complexity: O(n log n)

Space complexity: O(n) (due to temporary arrays)
